{"title_page": "Mysore Manjunath", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2017}}\n [[File:Mysore Manjunath violinist.jpg|thumb|Dr.Mysore Manjunath]] \n'''Mysore Manjunath'''  is an [[India]]n violinist.<ref>https://mysuru.com/mysoreBros.aspx</ref> The son and disciple of violinist Prof. Mahadevappa, Manjunath performed his first concert at the age of 8 in [[Mysore]] as a [[child prodigy]] storming in to the music world <ref>http://indiaepost.com/2018/07/29/world-renowned-violinist-dr-mysore-manjunath-to-perform-at-the-educational-institutes-in-dehradun-from-august-1-to-august-4-2018/</ref> Trained under his father, Manjunath,<ref>http://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20040828/saturday/main1.htm</ref> and brother Mysore Nagaraj, received special coaching in violin technique and improvisation. He is one of the [[Mysore brothers]] duo enthralling audiences around the world with his mellifluous music and astounding mastery of the violin <ref>https://www.deccanherald.com/content/549183/twice-prowess.html</ref>. He is honored with the prestigious [[Sangeet Natak Akademi]] Award by Govt. of India,bestowed by the Hon. President of India at The [[Rashtrapathi Bhavan]] in New Delhi<ref> https://starofmysore.com/selected-sangith-natak-academy-award/</ref>.\n\n\n\n==Education==\nManjunath did his Master of Music at the [[University of Mysore]] securing first Rank with 4 Gold Medals and was awarded Ph.D by the University of Mysore.<ref>https://www.news18.com/news/india/a-sonorous-journey-by-violin-maestros-377583.html</ref><ref>https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/honour-for-mysores-violin-maestros/article5665242.ece</ref>\n\n==Career==\nManjunath started performing at 8 and his initial concerts were with his father and brother.<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/raised-to-the-power-of-two/article27546520.ece</ref> He regularly performs along with his elder brother Mysore Nagaraj.<ref>http://mysuru.com/mysoreBros.aspx</ref>  His violin concerts are featured at major international concert stages including [[Royal Albert Hall]] - [[London]], [[Sydney Opera House]] - [[Australia]], International Violin Conference, Common Thread Music festival in [[United States]], [[Federation Square]] in [[Melbourne]], World Music Festival<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MVVSJL7k9ls</ref> in [[Chicago]],<ref>http://www.radioandmusic.com/content/editorial/news/zakir-hussain-niladri-kumar-open-chicago-world-music-festival</ref> [[Oxford University]]<ref>https://www.music.ox.ac.uk/event/the-mysore-brothers-2/</ref>, Tansen Sangith Samaroh-Gwalior,Esplanade Theatre in Singapore, World Music Series by [[BBC]], [[Santa-Fe Festival]]<ref>http://www.sfreporter.com/santafe/article-1735-performing-arts-books-june-27-july-3.html</ref> in [[New Mexico]],Persian Academy of Culture in [[Iran]] Doverlane Music Festival in Kolkata, [[India International Centre]]<ref>http://www.iicdelhi.in/webcasts/view_webcast/carnatic-violin-duet-by-the-mysore-brothers-/</ref>.  He has collaborated with musicians and orchestras including [[Ned McGowan]], [[Fabrizio Cassol]], Jai Uttal,  Joe Craven, Fred Hamilton, Todd Haaby, Pandith [[Vishwa Mohan Bhatt]], [[Ronu Majumdar]], [[N. Rajam]], Tejendra Majumdar such as [[Aka Moon]],<ref>http://www.akamoon.com/index.php?id=159{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Spenifex,<ref>http://www.womex.com/virtual/spinifex</ref> [[Ictus Ensemble|Ictus]].\n\nHe was nominated as cultural ambassador of University of Mysore.<ref>http://www.bangalorefirst.in/?p=13376</ref> Dr.Manjunath has created many New ragas including Yaduveera Manohari,<ref>https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/in-other-news/260616/yaduveer-raga-for-mysuru-royal-wedding.html</ref> Bharatha . His recent creation Yoga Anthem- having many popular world musicians performing in it, got nationwide recognition<ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mysuru/mysuru-musician-composes-anthem-for-international-yoga-day/articleshow/69864567.cms</ref>.<ref>https://www.asianage.com/life/more-features/210619/anthem-for-yoga.html</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nHe is one of the youngest recipients of the [[Sangeet Natak Akademi]]<ref>https://starofmysore.com/selected-sangith-natak-academy-award/</ref> award by the [[Government of India]] and the [[Rajyotsava Award]] by the Government of [[Karnataka]].<ref>http://www.thehindu.com/2003/10/31/stories/2003103101770600.htm</ref> He has received the Excellence award from [[American Institute of World Culture]], honours from the [[American Arts Council]], Best Violinist awards from The [[Music Academy]], Best Violinist award from the Indian fine arts society, Aryabhata Award, Meritorious Award from [[University of Oklahoma]]-USA,  Samskruthi Sinchana Award, Y.T.Tatachari National Award, Sangeeth Samrat, Sangeeth Rathna, Sangitha Vidwanmani, Gana varidhi, Tantri Vadya Shiromani - Asthana Vidwan from [[Sri Kanchi Kamakoti Peetham]], [[Chowdiah National Award]] by Academy of Music,<ref>http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/honour-for-musicians/article4132242.ece</ref> Rotary Excellence Award & Rama Ganakalacharya<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/mysore-brothers-to-receive-rama-gana-kalacharya-award/article23531128.ece</ref>, Sangeetha Vedanta Dhurina<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/honour-for-mysores-violin-maestros/article5665242.ece</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mysoremanjunath.com/ Official Website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Manjunath, Mysore}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Carnatic violinists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Mysore]]\n[[Category:University of Mysore alumni]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Indian male classical musicians]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Rajyotsava Award 2003]]\n[[Category:21st-century violinists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2017}}\n [[File:Mysore Manjunath violinist.jpg|thumb|Dr.Mysore Manjunath]] \n'''Mysore Manjunath'''  is an [[India]]n violinist.<ref>https://mysuru.com/mysoreBros.aspx</ref> The son and disciple of violinist Prof. Mahadevappa, Manjunath performed his first concert at the age of 8 in [[Mysore]] as a [[child prodigy]] storming in to the music world <ref>http://indiaepost.com/2018/07/29/world-renowned-violinist-dr-mysore-manjunath-to-perform-at-the-educational-institutes-in-dehradun-from-august-1-to-august-4-2018/</ref> Trained under his father, Manjunath,<ref>http://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20040828/saturday/main1.htm</ref> and brother Mysore Nagaraj, received special coaching in violin technique and improvisation. He is one of the [[Mysore brothers]] duo enthralling audiences around the world with his mellifluous music and astounding mastery of the violin <ref>https://www.deccanherald.com/content/549183/twice-prowess.html</ref>. He is honored with the prestigious [[Sangeet Natak Akademi]] Award by Govt. of India,bestowed by the Hon. President of India at The [[Rashtrapathi Bhavan]] in New Delhi<ref> https://starofmysore.com/selected-sangith-natak-academy-award/</ref>.\n\n\n\n==Education==\nManjunath did his Master of Music at the [[University of Mysore]] securing first Rank with 4 Gold Medals and was awarded Ph.D by the University of Mysore.<ref>https://www.news18.com/news/india/a-sonorous-journey-by-violin-maestros-377583.html</ref><ref>https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/honour-for-mysores-violin-maestros/article5665242.ece</ref>\n\n==Career==\nManjunath started performing at 8 and his initial concerts were with his father and brother.<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/raised-to-the-power-of-two/article27546520.ece</ref> He regularly performs along with his elder brother Mysore Nagaraj.<ref>http://mysuru.com/mysoreBros.aspx</ref>  His violin concerts are featured at major international concert stages including [[Royal Albert Hall]] - [[London]], [[Sydney Opera House]] - [[Australia]], International Violin Conference, Common Thread Music festival in [[United States]], [[Federation Square]] in [[Melbourne]], World Music Festival<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MVVSJL7k9ls</ref> in [[Chicago]],<ref>http://www.radioandmusic.com/content/editorial/news/zakir-hussain-niladri-kumar-open-chicago-world-music-festival</ref> [[Oxford University]]<ref>https://www.music.ox.ac.uk/event/the-mysore-brothers-2/</ref>, Tansen Sangith Samaroh-Gwalior,Esplanade Theatre in Singapore, World Music Series by [[BBC]], [[Santa-Fe Festival]]<ref>http://www.sfreporter.com/santafe/article-1735-performing-arts-books-june-27-july-3.html</ref> in [[New Mexico]],Persian Academy of Culture in [[Iran]] Doverlane Music Festival in Kolkata, [[India International Centre]]<ref>http://www.iicdelhi.in/webcasts/view_webcast/carnatic-violin-duet-by-the-mysore-brothers-/</ref>.  He has collaborated with musicians and orchestras including [[Ned McGowan]], [[Fabrizio Cassol]], Jai Uttal,  Joe Craven, Fred Hamilton, Todd Haaby, Pandith [[Vishwa Mohan Bhatt]], [[Ronu Majumdar]], [[N. Rajam]], Tejendra Majumdar such as [[Aka Moon]],<ref>http://www.akamoon.com/index.php?id=159{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Spenifex,<ref>http://www.womex.com/virtual/spinifex</ref> [[Ictus Ensemble|Ictus]].\n\nHe was nominated as cultural ambassador of University of Mysore.<ref>http://www.bangalorefirst.in/?p=13376</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nHe is one of the youngest recipients of the [[Sangeet Natak Akademi]]<ref>https://starofmysore.com/selected-sangith-natak-academy-award/</ref> award by the [[Government of India]] and the [[Rajyotsava Award]] by the Government of [[Karnataka]].<ref>http://www.thehindu.com/2003/10/31/stories/2003103101770600.htm</ref> He has received the Excellence award from [[American Institute of World Culture]], honours from the [[American Arts Council]], Best Violinist awards from The [[Music Academy]], Best Violinist award from the Indian fine arts society, Aryabhata Award, Meritorious Award from [[University of Oklahoma]]-USA,  Samskruthi Sinchana Award, Y.T.Tatachari National Award, Sangeeth Samrat, Sangeeth Rathna, Sangitha Vidwanmani, Gana varidhi, Tantri Vadya Shiromani - Asthana Vidwan from [[Sri Kanchi Kamakoti Peetham]], [[Chowdiah National Award]] by Academy of Music,<ref>http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/honour-for-musicians/article4132242.ece</ref> Rotary Excellence Award & Rama Ganakalacharya<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/mysore-brothers-to-receive-rama-gana-kalacharya-award/article23531128.ece</ref>, Sangeetha Vedanta Dhurina<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/honour-for-mysores-violin-maestros/article5665242.ece</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mysoremanjunath.com/ Official Website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Manjunath, Mysore}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Carnatic violinists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Mysore]]\n[[Category:University of Mysore alumni]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Indian male classical musicians]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Rajyotsava Award 2003]]\n[[Category:21st-century violinists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Manirang1975", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mysore_Manjunath"}
{"title_page": "Stereo 974", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2017}}\n{{refimprove|date=February 2009}}\n{{short description|Defunct radio station in Melbourne, Victoria}}\n{{Infobox Radio station\n|name               = Stereo 974\n|image              = File:Stereo 974 logo.gif\n|city               = [[Tottenham, Victoria]]\n|area               = [[Western Suburbs (Melbourne)|Melbourne Western Suburbs]]<ref name=\"acmamap\">{{cite web |title=MELBOURNE WEST RA1 |url=http://www.acma.gov.au/licplan/defmaps/documents/maps/la_352.pdf |website=Australian Communications and Media Authority |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303183802/http://www.acma.gov.au/licplan/defmaps/documents/maps/la_352.pdf |archivedate=3 May 2016 |format=PDF |date=27 March 2012}}</ref>\n|branding           = \n|slogan             = ''Your Station''\n|frequency          = {{Frequency|97.4|[[MHz]]}} [[FM broadcasting|FM]]\n|translator         = \n|repeater           = \n|airdate            = {{Start date and age|1978}}\n|last airdate       = {{End date and age|2020|01|16}}\n|share              = \n|share as of        = \n|share source       = \n|format             = [[Community radio]]\n|language           = [[Multilingual]]\n|power              = \n|erp                = 200 [[watt|W]]\n|haat               = \n|class              = \n|facility_id        = \n|coordinates        = \n|callsign_meaning   = '''3''' - Victorian<br />'''W'''estern '''R'''adio '''B'''roadcasters\n|former_callsigns   = \n|former_frequencies = \n|affiliations       = \n|owner              = Western Radio Broadcasters Ltd.\n|licensee           = \n|sister_stations    = \n|website            = \n}}\n\n'''Stereo 974''' (call sign: '''3WRB''') was an Australian [[community radio]] station broadcasting to the [[Western Suburbs (Melbourne)|western suburbs]] of [[Melbourne|Melbourne, Victoria]]. First broadcast in 1978<ref name=\"974floods\">{{cite news |title=Melbourne community station flooded |url=https://radioinfo.com.au/news/melbourne-community-station-flooded |accessdate=11 January 2020 |work=Radioinfo.com.au |date=27 June 2006}}</ref> from studios in [[Braybrook, Victoria|Braybrook]], at the time of closure the station was based in [[Brooklyn, Victoria|Brooklyn]] and broadcast a mix of [[country music]] and programming in [[languages other than English]] (LOTE).<ref name=\"974grid\">{{cite web |title=Program Grid |url=https://stereo974.com/program-grid/ |website=Stereo 974 |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nStereo 974 commenced broadcasting as '''3WRB''', initially covering a broader area; encompassing the [[Werribee, Victoria|Werribee]] and [[Melton, Victoria|Melton]] areas now served by [[3WYN|WYN FM]] and [[979fm]] respectively. Previous committee members include the then-Member for [[Division of Lalor|Lalor]], [[Barry Jones (Australian politician)|Barry Jones]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]], who served as chairman between 1980 and 1982.<ref name=\"974floods\"/>\n<!-- Western Region Broadcasting was changed to a corporation structure with a Board of Directors and membership but was fraught with problems and the committee was brought before the then Chairman of the Australian Broadcasting Tribunal, Mr. Peter Westaway at Naura House in the first instance and later at the Brimbank Council offices. When the Station Management and ABT agreed on new regulations, Western Region Broadcasters began providing local area broadcasting once again. <ref>David Sharpe JP</ref>The original committee consisted of Noel Grieg (President), David Sharpe JP (Vice-President), Anthony Cerantonio, Trudy Burke, George Eliades (Technical Engineer) and approx 200 members. The station started at a 40' shipping Container in Duke Street, Braybrook later moving to the West End Market in McIntyre Road, Sunshine and finally, under the new Management of Rod Boyd, to its current location at 594 Geelong Road, Brooklyn. \n\nFollowing on from there, the radio station was under the 3WRB banner once again. After many years of continued stability, the radio station publicly relaunched with a music / ethnic focus under  the brand name \"STEREO 974\". -->\n\nIn December 1990, the [[Australian Broadcasting Tribunal]] held a hearing to determine whether additional conditions should be placed on the 3WRB licence, or to suspend the station's licence entirely.<ref>{{cite report |date=1991 |title=Australian Broadcasting Tribunal: Annual Report 1990-91 |url=https://apo.org.au/sites/default/files/resource-files/1991/12/apo-nid63003-1221951.pdf |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Tribunal |page=30 |access-date=11 January 2020 }}</ref> Consequently, Western Radio Broadcasters was restructured from a [[corporation]] structure to a membership committee, and in 1992 the Tribunal ruled 3WRB would retain its licence,<ref>{{cite report |date=1992 |title=Australian Broadcasting Tribunal: Annual Report 1991-92 |url=https://apo.org.au/sites/default/files/resource-files/1992/12/apo-nid63005-1217526.pdf |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Tribunal |page=32 |access-date=11 January 2020 }}</ref> albeit with extra conditions including amendments to the licencee's constitution.<ref>{{cite report |date=1993 |title=Australian Broadcasting Tribunal: Report on activities 1992 |url=https://apo.org.au/sites/default/files/resource-files/1993/12/apo-nid63006-1210381.pdf |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Tribunal |page=28 |access-date=11 January 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, [[Southern Cross Broadcasting]], owners of commercial radio stations [[3AW]] and [[3MP]], sought a [[Federal Court of Australia|Federal Court]] injunction against 3WRB and [[3INR]] from broadcasting the [[1994 AFL season]]. 3WRB had intended to broadcast games featuring [[Western Bulldogs|Footscray]], as it did in the [[1993 AFL season|1993 season]]. The injunction was granted, however the [[Australian Broadcasting Authority]] (ABA) later ruled that both stations were not in breach of the [[Broadcasting Services Act 1992]]. In both cases, the broadcast of [[Australian Football League]] matches did not constitute a profit-making enterprise, and thus \"do[es] not change the nature of the service from community to commercial.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=AFL football broadcasts on community radio|url=http://www5.austlii.edu.au/au/journals/AUBAUpdateNlr/1994/96.pdf |website=ABA Update |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Authority}}</ref>\n\nWestern Radio Broadcasters was also found to have breached the Broadcasting Services Act and the [[Community Broadcasting Association of Australia]] (CBAA) Code of Practice on several occasions. In February 1999, the ABA found the station had breached clauses 6.3 and 6.4 of the CBAA code for its handling of a dispute between a presenter and the committee of management.<ref>{{cite report |date=February 1999 |title=ABA Update |url=http://classic.austlii.edu.au/au/journals/AUBAUpdateNlr/1999/20.pdf |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Authority |section=3WRB Melbourne denial of access and conflict resolution |page=21 |access-date=11 January 2020 }}</ref> The station was also found in breach of its community radio licence for broadcasting [[advertisements]] during episodes of its [[Vietnamese language]] program in April and May 2000 and July 2001.<ref>{{cite report |date=April 2001 |title=ABA Update |url=http://classic.austlii.edu.au/au/journals/AUBAUpdateNlr/2001/50.pdf |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Authority |section=3WRB - Melbourne: Broadcasting advertisements and sponsorship influencing programming |pages=20-21 |access-date=11 January 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite report |date=2002 |title=ABA Update |url=http://classic.austlii.edu.au/au/journals/AUBAUpdateNlr/2002/52.pdf |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Authority |section=3WRB - Melbourne: Sponsorship announcements in breach of licence conditions |page=18 |access-date=11 January 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, following the [[Coode Island#History|Coode Island fire]], the station established an [[emergency population warning|emergency warning system]].<ref>{{cite news |title=STEREO 974 GM Rod Boyd named Brimbank Council Citizen of the Year |url=https://radioinfo.com.au/news/stereo-974-gm-rod-boyd-named-brimbank-council-citizen-year |accessdate=11 January 2020 |work=Radioinfo.com.au |date=25 January 2018}}</ref> In 2010, the station signed a [[memorandum of understanding]] and was certified as an official emergency broadcaster in its Melbourne West license area.<ref name=\"acmamap\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=More community stations become Emergency Broadcasters in lead up to CBAA Conference |url=https://radioinfo.com.au/news/more-community-stations-become-emergency-broadcasters-lead-cbaa-conference |accessdate=11 January 2020 |work=Radioinfo.com.au |date=22 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Closure===\nOn 16 January 2020 the station ceased broadcasting. Management declined to comment to the ''[[Star News Group|Star Weekly]]''; the newspaper speculated that a lack of funding may have made the station financially nonviable.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Papworth |first1=Tate |title=Community loses its voice |url=https://brimbanknorthwest.starweekly.com.au/news/community-loses-its-voice/ |accessdate=16 January 2020 |work=Star Weekly |date=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Programming (at time of closure)==\nAt the time of closure, programming was presented by volunteer presenters. [[English language]] programs included country music shows and the long-running ''Let It Be Beatles'', which had aired on the station since 1992.<ref>{{cite news |title=Let it Be Beatles show on Stereo 974 been around longer than the band |url=https://radioinfo.com.au/news/let-it-be-beatles-show-stereo-974-been-around-longer-band |accessdate=11 January 2020 |work=Radioinfo.com.au |date=26 September 2011}}</ref> LOTE programming was produced in languages including [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Maltese language|Maltese]], [[Sudanese Arabic]], [[Sinhalese language|Sinhalese]] and [[Ethiopian language|Ethiopian]]. Funding for these programs was made available by the [[Community Broadcasting Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Volunteer training at 3WRB |url=https://cbf.org.au/stereo974-volunteer-training/ |publisher=Community Broadcasting Foundation |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nStereo 974 had won several awards from the [[Southern Community Media Association]], which incorporates community broadcasters from regional and suburban Australia.\n\n{{Awards table}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"4\" | 2009\n| Stereo 974\n| Best In House Production of a Sweeper\n| {{won}}<ref name=\"SCMA2009wins\">{{cite web |title=STEREO 974 \u2013 SCOOPS THE POOL AT SOUTHERN COMMUNITY MEDIA ASSOCIATION AWARDS. |url=https://stereo974.com/2009/04/16/stereo-974-scoops-the-pool-at-southern-community-media-association-awards/ |website=Stereo 974 |accessdate=16 January 2020 |date=16 April 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n| Stereo 974\n| Best In House Production of a Local Music Program\n| {{won}}<ref name=\"SCMA2009wins\"/>\n|-\n| Stereo 974\n| Best In House Production of a Station ID\n| {{nominated}}<ref name=\"SCMA2009wins\"/>\n|-\n| Stereo 974\n| Best In House Production of a Sponsorship Announcement\n| {{nominated}}<ref name=\"SCMA2009wins\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"7\" | 2013\n| Stereo 974\n| Best In House Production of a Sweeper or Station ID\n| {{won}}<ref name=\"SCMA2013wins\">{{cite news |title=SCMA award winners announced |url=https://radioinfo.com.au/news/scma-award-winners-announced |accessdate=11 January 2020 |work=Radioinfo.com.au |date=11 July 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| Stereo 974\n| Best In House Production of a Community Service Announcement\n| {{won}}<ref name=\"SCMA2013wins\"/>\n|-\n| Bob Taylor\n| Best Program \u2013 Music\n| {{won}}<ref name=\"SCMA2013wins\"/>\n|-\n| Bob Taylor\n| Best Interview\n| {{nominated}}<ref name=\"SCMA2013nom\">{{cite news |title=X award finalists announced |url=https://radioinfo.com.au/news/x-award-finalists-announced |accessdate=11 January 2020 |work=Radioinfo.com.au |date=10 June 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| Dave Dawson\n| Best Program \u2013 Non Music\n| {{nominated}}<ref name=\"SCMA2013nom\"/>\n|-\n| Stereo 974\n| Best In House Production of a Show Promo\n| {{nominated}}<ref name=\"SCMA2013nom\"/>\n|-\n| Stereo 974\n| Best Local News\n| {{nominated}}<ref name=\"SCMA2013nom\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2015\n| Stereo 974\n| Best In House Production of a Show Promo\n| {{won}}<ref>{{cite news |title=SCMA Conference and X Award winners |url=https://radioinfo.com.au/news/scma-conference-and-x-award-winners |accessdate=11 January 2020 |work=Radioinfo.com.au |date=13 June 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200116055004/https://stereo974.com/|date=16 January 2020|title=Stereo 974}}\n\n{{Melbourne FM}}\n\n{{coord missing|Victoria (Australia)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stereo 97.4}}\n[[Category:Radio stations in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1978]]\n[[Category:Radio stations disestablished in 2020]]\n[[Category:Defunct radio stations in Australia]]\n[[Category:1978 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:2020 disestablishments in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2017}}\n{{refimprove|date=February 2009}}\n{{short description|Defunct radio station in Melbourne, Victoria}}\n{{Infobox Radio station\n|name               = Stereo 974\n|image              = File:Stereo 974 logo.gif\n|city               = [[Tottenham, Victoria]]\n|area               = [[Western Suburbs (Melbourne)|Melbourne Western Suburbs]]<ref name=\"acmamap\">{{cite web |title=MELBOURNE WEST RA1 |url=http://www.acma.gov.au/licplan/defmaps/documents/maps/la_352.pdf |website=Australian Communications and Media Authority |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303183802/http://www.acma.gov.au/licplan/defmaps/documen