akistan]]\n* [[List of diplomatic missions of Pakistan]]\n* [[List of diplomatic missions in Karachi]]\n* [[Visa requirements for Pakistani citizens]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.mofa.gov.pk/ Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Pakistan]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110902012804/http://www.mofa.gov.pk/Blue_Book/BLUE_BOOK.htm Foreign missions in Pakistan]\n\n{{Diplomatic missions in Pakistan}}\n{{Foreign relations of Pakistan}}\n{{Asia topic|List of diplomatic missions in}}\n\n[[Category:Diplomatic missions in Pakistan| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of diplomatic missions by receiving country|Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Pakistan diplomacy-related lists|Diplomatic missions in Pakistan]]\n", "name_user": "\u015awi\u0119tokrzyskie3", "label": "safe", "comment": "edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_diplomatic_missions_in_Pakistan"}
{"title_page": "Royal Victoria Dock", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox historic site\n|name=Royal Victoria Dock\n|native_name=\n|native_language=\n|image=The building of Victoria docks.jpg\n|caption=The building of Victoria Dock\n|coordinates={{coord|51.505823|0.029714|display=inline,title|region:GB_type:landmark}}\n|gbgridref=\n|location=[[London]]\n|built=1855\n|built_for=\n|demolished=\n|locmapin=United Kingdom London Newham\n|architect=[[George Parker Bidder]]\n}}\nThe '''Royal Victoria Dock''' is the largest of three [[Dock (maritime)|dock]]s in the [[Royal Docks]] of east London, now part of the redeveloped [[London Docklands|Docklands]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Victoria Docks 1872.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Map c1872, showing Victoria Docks, now Royal Victoria Dock, [[Bow Creek (England)|Bow Creek]] and the [[Thames Ironworks and Shipbuilding Company]]]]\n[[File:Canning Town and Royal Victoria Dock 1908.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Map 1908, showing [[Canning Town]], Royal Victoria Dock, part of [[Royal Albert Dock, London|Royal Albert Dock]]]]\nThe Royal Victoria Docks are {{convert|14|km|mi}} from [[London Bridge]], and {{convert|36|km|mi}} from Gravesend,<ref name=Naib/>{{rp|17}} and were designed and engineered by [[George Parker Bidder]].<ref name=Naib>{{cite book| title=London Docklands: Past, Present and Future| last=Al Naib| first= S.K.| publisher=[[University of East London]]| date=July 1990}}</ref>{{rp|3}} Although the structure was in place in the year 1850, it was opened in 1855 on a previously uninhabited area of the Plaistow Marshes, it was the first of the Royal Docks and the first London dock to be designed specifically to accommodate large steam ships. It was also the first to use hydraulic power to operate its machinery and the first to be connected to the national railway network via the [[Eastern Counties and Thames Junction Railway]] section of what is now the [[North London Line]].<ref name='portcitiesdock' /> It was initially known as \"Victoria Dock\"; the prefix \"Royal\" was granted in 1880.<ref name=RVD>{{cite web|title=Royal Victoria Dock|url=http://www.royaldockstrust.org.uk/popup.htm|publisher=Royal Docks Trust|accessdate=16 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe dock was connected to the national rail network via a line which ran between [[Canning Town]] and [[North Woolwich]].<ref name='northwoolwichline' /><ref name='westhamintro'>{{cite journal | title = West Ham: Introduction | journal = A History of the County of Essex: Volume 6 | year = 1973 | pages = 43\u201350| editors = W.R. Powell | url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=42748 | accessdate = 2011-02-28}}</ref> When the Royal Dock was first built the railway cut along the docks; to correct this a swingbridge over the entrance to the dock was built. This however slowed down journey time, and so a new line was built in 1855 to take the route around the north side of the dock to Silvertown, and a station at Custom House opened where it re-connected with the original line. The older southern line was kept to serve local factories, where it was known as the Silvertown Tramway.<ref name='portcitiesdock'>{{cite web|title=Royal Victoria Dock (1855\u20131981)|author=PortCities London|publisher=PortCities UK|url=http://www.portcities.org.uk/london/server/show/ConFactFile.73/Royal-Victoria-Dock.html|accessdate=3 September 2010}}</ref><ref name='northwoolwichline'>{{Cite web | url=http://www.urban75.org/railway/north-woolwich-line.html |title = A short history of the North Woolwich branch, Silvertown station and North Woolwich Railway, North Woolwich, London Docks, east London, UK}}</ref>\n\nThe Royal Victoria Dock consisted of a main dock and a basin to the west, providing an entrance to the Thames on the western side of the complex. The dock was deeply indented with four solid piers, each 152 m long by 43 m wide, on which were constructed two-storey warehouses. Other warehouses, granaries, shed and storage buildings surrounded the dock, which had a total of 3.6&nbsp;km of quays.<ref name=Naib/>{{rp|17}}\n\nThe dock was an immediate commercial success, as it could easily accommodate all but the very largest steamships. By 1860, it was already taking over 850,000 tons of shipping a year \u2013 double that of the [[London Docks]], four times that of [[St Katharine Docks]] and 70% more than the [[West India Docks|West India Dock]] and [[East India Docks]] combined. It was badly damaged by German bombing in [[World War II]] but experienced a resurgence in trade following the war. From the 1960s onwards, the Royal Victoria experienced a steady decline \u2013 as did all of London's other docks \u2013 as the shipping industry adopted [[containerisation]], which effectively moved traffic downstream to [[Port of Tilbury|Tilbury]]. It finally closed to commercial traffic along with the other Royal Docks in 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.londonsroyaldocks.com/londons-royal-docks-history/|title= History|publisher=London's Royal Docks|accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, the then-dilapidated site was chosen by French electronic musician [[Jean Michel Jarre]] as the site for one of his signature large-scale concerts, eventually titled [[Destination Docklands]]. The area also inspired him to write the album [[Revolutions (Jean Michel Jarre album)|''Revolutions'']] specifically for the event.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.muzines.co.uk/articles/docklands-rendezvous/354|title=Docklands Rendezvous|work=Music Technology|pages=26-31|date=August 1988|issn=0896-2480|oclc=16461726}}</ref>\n\nThe Royal Victoria Dock experienced major redevelopment initiated by the [[London Docklands Development Corporation]] in the 1990s. Developments included Britannia Village which was carried out by [[George Wimpey|Wimpey Homes]], the [[Peabody Trust]] and the [[East Thames housing association|East Thames Housing Group]] in the mid-1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faithinthedock.com/royal-docks-area/britannia-village/|title=Britannia Village|publisher=Faith in the Dock|accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nMost of the original buildings were demolished but a few historic warehouses survived.<ref>{{NHLE|desc=Warehouse W|num=1376227|accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref> More recent development has included the [[Royal Victoria Dock Bridge]] completed in 1998<ref>{{Structurae|id=20000610|title=Royal Victoria Dock Pedestrian Bridge}}. Retrieved 12 November 2005</ref> and the [[ExCeL London|ExCeL Exhibition Centre]], constructed on the north quayside, which opened in November 2000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wes-group.com/news.html |title=News from Worldwide |publisher=Worldwide Exhibition Specialists Ltd. |accessdate=11 July 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080315144211/http://www.wes-group.com/news.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 15 March 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\nOn 15 August 2009, the dock hosted the inaugural [[Great Swim|Great London Swim]], a mass participation open water swim over a one-mile distance. The event has been held annually since then but on the first weekend in July.\nOn 16-17 June 2018 was held the [[Formula 1 Powerboat World Championship|F1H2O]] Grand Prix of London.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.f1h2o.com/post/erik-stark-wins-a-pulsating-uim-f1h2o-grand-prix-of-london |title = F1H2O UIM World Championship: ERIK STARK WINS a PULSATING UIM F1H2O GRAND PRIX OF LONDON}}</ref> Britannia Village has its own Community Foundation.<ref>[http://www.westsilvertownfoundation.org.uk/ West Silvertown Online<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Royal Victoria Dock 1973.jpg|Looking west from Connaught Road swing bridge in 1973\nImage:Royal Albert dock looking west to CW.jpg|Looking west towards [[Canary Wharf]]\nImage:Royal Albert dock looking east towards city airport.jpg|Looking east to [[London City Airport]]\nImage:Im1934BCI-Spil24.jpg|Spiller's [[Millennium Mills]] in 1934. Behind is the Graving Dock\nImage:Royal Albert dock looking south at Spillers Mills & new dev.jpg|Looking south: some new development but Spillers Mills in need of renovation\nImage:Royal Victoria Dock looking south at cranes.jpg|Looking south: some new development and cranes as memory of the past\nImage:Tatefromspillers.jpeg|Looking east-south-east from the top of Spillers Millennium Mills\nImage:Royal Victoria Dock London.jpg|Looking east towards the [[ExCeL London|ExCeL Exhibition Centre]]\nImage:08-14-05 Royal Victoria Dock.jpg|[[The O2]] and [[Canary Wharf]] from the Royal Victoria Dock\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[King George V Dock, London|King George V Dock]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.royal-docks.co.uk  Royal Docks Forum]\n* [http://www.britanniavillage.org.uk Britannia Village Residents Forum]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nev3LDHL_tM London Landscape TV episode (6 mins) about Royal Victoria Dock]\n* [http://www.royaldocks.net  Royal Docks Information]\n\n{{Commons category|Royal Victoria Dock}}\n\n[[Category:London docks]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the London Borough of Newham]]\n[[Category:Geography of the London Borough of Newham]]\n[[Category:Port of London]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox historic site\n|name=Royal Victoria Dock\n|native_name=\n|native_language=\n|image=The building of Victoria docks.jpg\n|caption=The building of Victoria Dock\n|coordinates={{coord|51.505823|0.029714|display=inline,title|region:GB_type:landmark}}\n|gbgridref=\n|location=[[London]]\n|built=1855\n|built_for=\n|demolished=\n|locmapin=United Kingdom London Newham\n|architect=[[George Parker Bidder]]\n}}\nThe '''Royal Victoria Dock''' is the largest of three docks in the [[Royal Docks]] of east London, now part of the redeveloped [[London Docklands|Docklands]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Victoria Docks 1872.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Map c