ect this a swingbridge over the entrance to the dock was built. This however slowed down journey time, and so a new line was built in 1855 to take the route around the north side of the dock to Silvertown, and a station at Custom House opened where it re-connected with the original line. The older southern line was kept to serve local factories, where it was known as the Silvertown Tramway.<ref name='portcitiesdock'>{{cite web|title=Royal Victoria Dock (1855\u20131981)|author=PortCities London|publisher=PortCities UK|url=http://www.portcities.org.uk/london/server/show/ConFactFile.73/Royal-Victoria-Dock.html|accessdate=3 September 2010}}</ref><ref name='northwoolwichline'>{{Cite web | url=http://www.urban75.org/railway/north-woolwich-line.html |title = A short history of the North Woolwich branch, Silvertown station and North Woolwich Railway, North Woolwich, London Docks, east London, UK}}</ref>\n\nThe Royal Victoria Dock consisted of a main dock and a basin to the west, providing an entrance to the Thames on the western side of the complex. The dock was deeply indented with four solid piers, each 152 m long by 43 m wide, on which were constructed two-storey warehouses. Other warehouses, granaries, shed and storage buildings surrounded the dock, which had a total of 3.6&nbsp;km of quays.<ref name=Naib/>{{rp|17}}\n\nThe dock was an immediate commercial success, as it could easily accommodate all but the very largest steamships. By 1860, it was already taking over 850,000 tons of shipping a year \u2013 double that of the [[London Docks]], four times that of [[St Katharine Docks]] and 70% more than the [[West India Docks|West India Dock]] and [[East India Docks]] combined. It was badly damaged by German bombing in [[World War II]] but experienced a resurgence in trade following the war. From the 1960s onwards, the Royal Victoria experienced a steady decline \u2013 as did all of London's other docks \u2013 as the shipping industry adopted [[containerisation]], which effectively moved traffic downstream to [[Port of Tilbury|Tilbury]]. It finally closed to commercial traffic along with the other Royal Docks in 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.londonsroyaldocks.com/londons-royal-docks-history/|title= History|publisher=London's Royal Docks|accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, the then-dilapidated site was chosen by French electronic musician [[Jean Michel Jarre]] as the site for one of his signature large-scale concerts, eventually titled [[Destination Docklands]]. The area also inspired him to write the album [[Revolutions (Jean Michel Jarre album)|''Revolutions'']] specifically for the event.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.muzines.co.uk/articles/docklands-rendezvous/354|title=Docklands Rendezvous|work=Music Technology|pages=26-31|date=August 1988|issn=0896-2480|oclc=16461726}}</ref>\n\nThe Royal Victoria Dock experienced major redevelopment initiated by the [[London Docklands Development Corporation]] in the 1990s. Developments included Britannia Village which was carried out by [[George Wimpey|Wimpey Homes]], the [[Peabody Trust]] and the [[East Thames housing association|East Thames Housing Group]] in the mid-1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faithinthedock.com/royal-docks-area/britannia-village/|title=Britannia Village|publisher=Faith in the Dock|accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nMost of the original buildings were demolished but a few historic warehouses survived.<ref>{{NHLE|desc=Warehouse W|num=1376227|accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref> More recent development has included the [[Royal Victoria Dock Bridge]] completed in 1998<ref>{{Structurae|id=20000610|title=Royal Victoria Dock Pedestrian Bridge}}. Retrieved 12 November 2005</ref> and the [[ExCeL London|ExCeL Exhibition Centre]], constructed on the north quayside, which opened in November 2000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wes-group.com/news.html |title=News from Worldwide |publisher=Worldwide Exhibition Specialists Ltd. |accessdate=11 July 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080315144211/http://www.wes-group.com/news.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 15 March 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\nOn 15 August 2009, the dock hosted the inaugural [[Great Swim|Great London Swim]], a mass participation open water swim over a one-mile distance. The event has been held annually since then but on the first weekend in July.\nOn 16-17 June 2018 was held the [[Formula 1 Powerboat World Championship|F1H2O]] Grand Prix of London.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.f1h2o.com/post/erik-stark-wins-a-pulsating-uim-f1h2o-grand-prix-of-london |title = F1H2O UIM World Championship: ERIK STARK WINS a PULSATING UIM F1H2O GRAND PRIX OF LONDON}}</ref> Britannia Village has its own Community Foundation.<ref>[http://www.westsilvertownfoundation.org.uk/ West Silvertown Online<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Royal Victoria Dock 1973.jpg|Looking west from Connaught Road swing bridge in 1973\nImage:Royal Albert dock looking west to CW.jpg|Looking west towards [[Canary Wharf]]\nImage:Royal Albert dock looking east towards city airport.jpg|Looking east to [[London City Airport]]\nImage:Im1934BCI-Spil24.jpg|Spiller's [[Millennium Mills]] in 1934. Behind is the Graving Dock\nImage:Royal Albert dock looking south at Spillers Mills & new dev.jpg|Looking south: some new development but Spillers Mills in need of renovation\nImage:Royal Victoria Dock looking south at cranes.jpg|Looking south: some new development and cranes as memory of the past\nImage:Tatefromspillers.jpeg|Looking east-south-east from the top of Spillers Millennium Mills\nImage:Royal Victoria Dock London.jpg|Looking east towards the [[ExCeL London|ExCeL Exhibition Centre]]\nImage:08-14-05 Royal Victoria Dock.jpg|[[The O2]] and [[Canary Wharf]] from the Royal Victoria Dock\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[King George V Dock, London|King George V Dock]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.royal-docks.co.uk  Royal Docks Forum]\n* [http://www.britanniavillage.org.uk Britannia Village Residents Forum]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nev3LDHL_tM London Landscape TV episode (6 mins) about Royal Victoria Dock]\n* [http://www.royaldocks.net  Royal Docks Information]\n\n{{Commons category|Royal Victoria Dock}}\n\n[[Category:London docks]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the London Borough of Newham]]\n[[Category:Geography of the London Borough of Newham]]\n[[Category:Port of London]]\n", "name_user": "Rhynhardtk", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added link to WP page for 'Dock'", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Victoria_Dock"}
{"title_page": "Russula cyanoxantha", "text_new": "{{taxobox\n| image = Russula cyanoxantha.JPG\n| image_caption = ''Russula cyanoxantha''\n| regnum = [[Fungi]]\n| divisio = [[Basidiomycota]]\n| classis= [[Agaricomycetes]]\n| ordo = [[Russulales]]\n| familia = [[Russulaceae]]\n| genus = ''[[Russula]]''\n| species = '''''R. cyanoxantha'''''\n| binomial = ''Russula cyanoxantha''\n| binomial_authority = ([[Jacob Christian Sch\u00e4ffer|Schaeff.]]) [[Elias Magnus Fries|Fr.]]\n}}\n{{mycomorphbox\n| name = ''Russula cyanoxantha''\n| whichGills = adnate\n| capShape = flat\n| capShape2= convex\n| hymeniumType=gills\n| stipeCharacter=bare\n| ecologicalType=mycorrhizal\n| sporePrintColor=white\n| howEdible=choice\n}}\n\n'''''Russula cyanoxantha''''',  synonymous with '''R. xyanoxantha''', commonly known as the '''charcoal burner''', is a [[basidiomycete]] [[mushroom]], distinguished from most other members of the genus ''[[Russula]]'' by the fact that its [[gill (mushroom)|gill]]s do not split, but are soft and flexible. It is one of the most common species of ''Russula'' in [[Europe]].\n\nIt is an [[edible mushroom]]. It was designated \"Mushroom of the Year\" in 1997 by the [[German Association of Mycology]].\n\n== Description ==\nThe most salient characteristic is the weak gills, which feel greasy to the touch, are flexible and do not break. The cap is 4\u201315&nbsp;cm (1.5\u20136&nbsp;in) wide, convex at first and later flattened, and greenish to bright brown (they vary considerably in color). The stipe is pure white, slightly convex underneath, up to 10&nbsp;cm in height and 1.5\u20132.5&nbsp;cm (0.5\u20131&nbsp;in) in diameter. The spores are pure white. The stipe will give a green reaction when rubbed with iron salts (Ferrous Sulphate). Most other (but not all) russula species give a salmon reaction. Coupled with the gill flexibility this is a good diagnostic clue to species level.\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\n''Russula cyanoxantha'' grows in slightly acidic, but nutrient-rich soil. Like all ''Russulas'', it is a  [[mycorrhizal fungus]]. It is found most commonly in [[beech]] forests, and often in deciduous or mixed forests, appearing from May to November, with the highest concentration in July to September.\n\n==Use==\nThe [[edible mushroom]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Phillips |first=Roger |title=Mushrooms and Other Fungi of North America |year=2010 |origyear=2005 |publisher=Firefly Books |location=Buffalo, NY |isbn=978-1-55407-651-2 |p=137}}</ref> is suitable for many kinds of preparation; the flesh is not as hard as that of many other edible Russulas. It has a mild, nutty taste.\n\n==Similar species==\nThe cap of the grey-green Russula [[Russula grisea]] is more blue-grey but has violet or green hues with light cream gills. This fungus also grows in mixed forests, particularly under beech, and more rarely in coniferous forests.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Russula species|List of ''Russula'' species]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n*E. Garnweidner. ''Mushrooms and Toadstools of Britain and Europe''. Collins. 1994.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikispecies}}\n{{Commons|Russula cyanoxantha|Russula cyanoxantha}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060907234148/http://www.mtsn.tn.it/russulales-news/tx_photos.asp?index=5391 Russulales News page on ''Russula cyanoxantha'']\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q246696}}\n\n[[Category:Russula|cyanoxantha]]\n[[Category:Fungi of Europe]]\n[[Category:Edible fungi]]\n", "text_old": "{{taxobox\n| image = Russula cyanoxantha.JPG\n| image_caption = ''Russula cyanoxantha''\n| regnum = [[Fungi]]\n| divisio = [[Basidiomycota]]\n| classis= [[Agaricomycetes]]\n| ordo = [[Russulales]]\n| familia = [[Russulaceae]]\n| genus = ''[[Russula]]''\n| species = '''''R. cyanoxantha'''''\n| binomial = ''Russula cyanoxantha''\n| binomial_authority = ([[Jacob Christian Sch\u00e4ffer|Schaeff.]]) [[Elias Magnus Fries|Fr.]]\n}}\n{{mycomorphbox\n| name = ''Russula cyanoxantha''\n| whichGills = adnate\n| capShape = flat\n| capShape2= convex\n| hymeniumType=gills\n| stipeCharacter=bare\n| ecologicalType=mycorrhizal\n| sporePrintColor=white\n| howEdible=choice\n}}\n\n'''''Russula cyanoxantha''''',  synonymous with '''R. xyanoxantha''', commonly known as the '''charcoal burner''', is a [[basidiomycete]] [[mushroom]], distinguished from most other members of the genus ''[[Russula]]'' by the fact that its [[gill (mushroom)|gill]]s do not split, but are soft and flexible. It is one of the most common species of ''Russula'' in [[Europe]].\n\nIt is an [[edible mushroom]]. It was designated \"Mushroom of the Year\" in 1997 by the [[German Association of Mycology]].\n\n== Description ==\nThe most salient characteristic is the weak gills, which feel greasy to the touch, are flexible and do not break. The cap is 4\u201315&nbsp;cm (1.5\u20136&nbsp;in) wide, convex at first and later flattened, and greenish to bright brown (they vary considerably in color). The stipe is pure white, slightly convex underneath, up to 10&nbsp;cm in height and 1.5\u20132.5&nbsp;cm (0.5\u20131&nbsp;in) in diameter. The spores are pure white. The stipe will give a green reaction when rubbed with iron salts (Ferrous Sulphate). Most other (but not all) russula species give a salmon reaction. Coupled with the gill flexibility this is a good diagnostic clue to species level.\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\n''Russula cyanoxantha'' grows in slightly acidic, but nutrient-rich soil. Like all ''Russulas'', it is a  [[mycorrhizal fungus]]. It is found most commonly in [[beech]] forests, and often in deciduous or mixed forests, appearing from May to November, with the highest concentration in July to September.\n\n==Use==\nThe [[edible mushroom]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Phillips |first=Roger |title=Mushrooms and Other Fungi of North America |year=2010 |origyear=2005 |publisher=Firefly Books |location=Buffalo, NY |isbn=978-1-55407-651-2 |p=137}}</ref> is suitable for many kinds of preparation; the flesh is not as hard as that of many other edible Russulas. It has a mild, nutty taste.\n\n==Similar species==\nThe cap of the grey-green Russula [[Russula grisea]] is more blue-grey but has violet or green hues with light cream gills. This fungus also grows in mixed forests, particularly under beech, and more rarely in coniferous forests.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Russula species|List of ''Russula'' species]]\n\n==References==\n*E. Garnweidner. ''Mushrooms and Toadstools of Britain and Europe''. Collins. 1994.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikispecies}}\n{{Commons|Russula cyanoxantha|Russula cyanoxantha}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060907234148/http://www.mtsn.tn.it/russulales-news/tx_photos.asp?index=5391 Russulales News page on ''Russula cyanoxantha'']\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q246696}}\n\n[[Category:Russula|cyanoxantha]]\n[[Category:Fungi of Europe]]\n[[Category:Edible fungi]]\n", "name_user": "UpdateNerd", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russula_cyanoxantha"}
{"title_page": "Mary Carr", "text_new": "{{About|the actress|the author|Mary Jane Carr|the author and poet|Mary Karr}}\n{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Mary Carr\n| image        = Mary Carr Stars of the Photoplay.jpg\n| caption      = ''Stars of the Photoplay'', 1924\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1874|3|14}}\n| birth_place  = [[Germantown, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Germantown, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1973|6|24|1874|3|14}}\n| death_place  = [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles]], U.S.\n| years_active = 1915&ndash;1956\n| occupation   = Actress\n}}\n\n'''Mary Carr''' (n\u00e9e Kenevan) (March 14, 1874 &ndash; June 24, 1973), was an American film actress and was married to the actor William Carr (1866\u20131937). She appeared in 144 films between 1915 and 1956. She was given some of filmdoms plum mother roles in silent pictures, especially Fox's 1920 ''[[Over the Hill to the Poorhouse]]'' which was a great success.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=634NAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA72&dq=mary+carr+over+the+hill+to+the+poorhouse&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiDoKTJ25boAhXdGDQIHWopDlEQ6AEIPDAD#v=onepage&q=mary%20carr%20over%20the%20hill%20to%20the%20poorhouse|title=Photoplay: The Aristocrat of Motion Picture Magazines|date=1920|publisher=Photoplay Magazine Publishing Company|language=en}}</ref> She was interred in [[Calvary Cemetery, East Los Angeles|Calvary Cemetery]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Wilson|first=Scott|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7-DgDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA752&lpgMary%20carr&f=false#v=onepage&q=Mary%20carr&f=false|title=Resting Places: The Burial Sites of More Than 14,000 Famous Persons, 3d ed.|date=2016-08-17|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-7992-4|language=en}}</ref> Carr bore a strong resemblance to [[Lucy Beaumont (actress)|Lucy Beaumont]], another famous character actress of the time who specialized in mother roles. As older actresses such as [[Mary Maurice]] and [[Anna Townsend]] passed on, Carr, still in her forties, seem to inherit all the matriarchal roles in silent films.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Slide|first=Anthony|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uznsDu6OHA0C&pg=PA55&dq=mary+carr+actress&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiAmp7V1pboAhUkLX0KHeUPDvI4ChDoATABegQIARAM#v=onepage&q=mary%20carr%20actress&f=false|title=Silent Players: A Biographical and Autobiographical Study of 100 Silent Film Actors and Actresses|date=2010-02-01|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=978-0-8131-3745-2|language=en}}</ref>\n\nMary Carr appeared on the June 9, 1954 episode of the radio quiz program \"[[You Bet Your Life]]\", hosted by comedian [[Groucho Marx]].<ref>https://archive.org/details/YouBetYourLife1</ref>\n\nThe Carrs' oldest son, William (1902\u201304), died at two years of age. Almost all of her children were involved in the film business and appeared with her in ''Over the Hill''.<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9F01E3DF1F31E433A2575BC1A96F9C946195D6CF NY Times: The Screen September 18, 1920 announcing the premier screening of ''Over the Hill'' with Mary Carr and her children]</ref>  They are as follows:\n*John Carr (January 2, 1904 \u2013 November 27, 1956)\n*Stephen Carr (April 23, 1906 \u2013 May 20, 1986)\n*[[Thomas Carr (director)|Thomas Carr]] (July 4, 1907 \u2013 April 23, 1997)\n*Rosemary Carr (October 2, 1910 \u2013 April 24, 1987)\n*Maybeth (Mary Elizabeth) Carr (May 4, 1912 \u2013 December 27, 1996) m. [[Pete Carpenter]]\n*Marie Luella Carr Walsh (October 18, 1899 \u2013 January 16, 1937)\n\n==Filmography==\n===Silent films===\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* ''[[The Shadow of Tragedy]]'' (1915 short)\n* ''[[The Mirror (1915 film)|The Mirror]]'' (1915 short) as Mrs. Carr\n* ''[[Blaming the Duck, or Ducking the Blame]]'' (1915 short) as Mrs. Carr\n* ''[[The City of Failing Light]]'' (1916) as Mrs. William Carr, '''lost'''\n* ''[[Souls in Bondage]]'' (1916) as Mrs. Carr, '''lost'''\n* ''[[Her Bleeding Heart]]'' (1916) as Mrs. Carr, '''lost'''\n* ''[[The Flames of Johannis]]'' (1916) as Mrs. Carr, '''lost'''\n* ''[[Love's Toll]]'' (1916) as Mrs. Carr, '''lost'''\n* ''[[The Light at Dusk]]'' (1916) as Mary Kennevan Carr, '''lost'''\n* ''[[The Barrier (1917 film)|The Barrier]]'' (1917) as Mary Kennevan Carr, '''lost'''\n* ''[[The Beloved Rogue (1918 film)|The Beloved Rogue]]'' (1918) '''lost''' (not to be confused with 1917 film ''[[Beloved Rogues]]'')\n* ''[[The Sign Invisible]]'' (1918) as Mary Kennevan Carr, '''lost'''\n* ''[[My Own United States]]'' (1918) as Mary Kennevan Carr, '''lost'''\n* ''[[To the Highest Bidder]]'' (1918) '''lost'''\n* ''[[The Birth of a Race]]'' (1918) as Mary K. Carr, '''extant'''\n* ''[[The Lion and the Mouse (1919 film)|The Lion and the Mouse]]'' (1919) '''lost'''\n* ''[[Mrs. Wiggs of the Cabbage Patch (1919 film)|Mrs. Wiggs of the Cabbage Patch]]'' (1919) '''extant''', in the Library of Congress\n* ''[[Calibre 38]]'' (1919) as Mary Kennevan Carr, '''incomplete''', Library of Congress\n* ''[[The Spark Divine]]'' (1919) '''lost'''\n* ''[[Over the Hill to the Poorhouse]]'' (1920) '''extant'''\n* ''[[Thunderclap (1921 film)|Thunderclap]]'' (1921) '''lost'''\n* ''[[Silver Wings (film)|Silver Wings]]'' (1922) '''lost'''\n* ''[[The Custard Cup]]'' (1923) '''lost'''\n* ''[[You Are Guilty]]'' (1923) '''extant''', may be the LOC Kodascope abridged version\n* ''[[Loyal Lives]]'' (1923) '''extant''', incomplete or abridged\n* ''[[The Daring Years]]'' (1923) '''lost'''\n* ''[[On the Banks of the Wabash (1923 film)|On the Banks of the Wabash]]'' (1923) (*abridged version exists;private collector)\n* ''[[Broadway Broke]]'' (1923) '''Lost'''\n* ''[[Three O'Clock in the Morning (film)|Three O'Clock in the Morning]]'' (1923) '''lost'''\n* ''[[Roulette (1924 film)|Roulette]]'' (1924) '''lost'''\n* ''[[Painted People]]'' (1924) '''lost'''\n* ''[[Damaged Hearts]]'' (1924) '''lost'''\n* ''[[Why Men Leave Home]]'' (1924) '''extant''', MGM and/or George Eastman House\n* ''[[The Woman on the Jury]]'' (1924) '''lost''' \n* ''[[The Spirit of the USA]]'' (1924) '''extant''', abridged version\n* ''[[For Sale (1924 film)|For Sale]]'' (1924) '''lost'''\n* ''[[A Self-Made Failure]]'' (1924) '''lost''', trailer only in the Library of Congress\n* ''[[The Mine with the Iron Door (1924 film)|The Mine with the Iron Door]]'' (1924) '''extant''', Gosfilmofond and Bois d'Arcy, France\n* ''[[Three Women (1924 film)|Three Women]]'' (1924) '''extant'''\n* ''[[East of Broadway]]'' (1924) '''extant''', Cineteca Italiana\n* ''[[On the Stroke of Three]]'' (1924) '''lost'''\n* ''[[Easy Money (1925 film)|Easy Money]]'' (1925) '''extant''', Library of Congress\n* ''[[Capital Punishment (film)|Capital Punishment]]'' (1925) '''extant''', Filmmuseum Amsterdam and UCLA Film and Television Archive\n* ''[[The Parasite (1925 film)|The Parasite]]'' (1925) '''extant''', Library of Congress\n* ''[[The Night Ship]]'' (1925) '''lost'''\n* ''[[The Re-Creation of Brian Kent]]'' (1925) '''extant'''', Library of Congress\n* ''[[School for Wives (1925 film)|School for Wives]]'' (1925) '''lost'''\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1925 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' (1925) as [[Aunt Em]], '''extant'''\n* ''[[Go Straight]]'' (1925) '''extant''', Library of Congress\n* ''[[Drusilla with a Million]]'' (1925) '''extant''', Lobster Films, France\n* ''[[A Slave of Fashion]]'' (1925) '''lost'''\n* ''[[The Fighting Cub]]'' (1925) '''extant''', UCLA (one reel missing)\n* ''[[His Master's Voice (1925 film)|His Master's Voice]]'' (1925) '''extant''', Grapevine Video\n* ''[[Big Pal]]'' (1925) '''extant'''\n* ''[[The Red Kimona]]'' (1925) '''extant''', Library of Congress\n* ''[[Hogan's Alley (1925 film)|Hogan's Alley]]'' (1925) '''extant'''\n* ''[[Flaming Waters]]'' (1925) '''extant''', Library of Congress\n* ''[[The Gold Hunters]]'' (1925) '''lost'''\n* ''[[Stop, Look and Listen (film)|Stop, Look and Listen]]'' (1926) '''lost'''\n* ''[[