9e Kenevan) (March 14, 1874 &ndash; June 24, 1973), was an American film actress and was married to the actor William Carr (1866\u20131937). She appeared in 144 films between 1915 and 1956. She was given some of filmdoms plum mother roles in silent pictures, especially Fox's 1920 ''[[Over the Hill to the Poorhouse]]'' which was a great success.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=634NAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA72&dq=mary+carr+over+the+hill+to+the+poorhouse&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiDoKTJ25boAhXdGDQIHWopDlEQ6AEIPDAD#v=onepage&q=mary%20carr%20over%20the%20hill%20to%20the%20poorhouse|title=Photoplay: The Aristocrat of Motion Picture Magazines|date=1920|publisher=Photoplay Magazine Publishing Company|language=en}}</ref> She was interred in [[Calvary Cemetery, East Los Angeles|Calvary Cemetery]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Wilson|first=Scott|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7-DgDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA752&lpgMary%20carr&f=false#v=onepage&q=Mary%20carr&f=false|title=Resting Places: The Burial Sites of More Than 14,000 Famous Persons, 3d ed.|date=2016-08-17|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-7992-4|language=en}}</ref> Carr bore a strong resemblance to [[Lucy Beaumont (actress)|Lucy Beaumont]], another famous character actress of the time who specialized in mother roles. As older actresses such as [[Mary Maurice]] and [[Anna Townsend]] passed on, Carr, still in her forties, seem to inherit all the matriarchal roles in silent films.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Slide|first=Anthony|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uznsDu6OHA0C&pg=PA55&dq=mary+carr+actress&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiAmp7V1pboAhUkLX0KHeUPDvI4ChDoATABegQIARAM#v=onepage&q=mary%20carr%20actress&f=false|title=Silent Players: A Biographical and Autobiographical Study of 100 Silent Film Actors and Actresses|date=2010-02-01|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=978-0-8131-3745-2|language=en}}</ref>\n\nMary Carr appeared on the June 9, 1954 episode of the radio quiz program \"[[You Bet Your Life]]\", hosted by comedian [[Groucho Marx]].<ref>https://archive.org/details/YouBetYourLife1</ref>\n\nThe Carrs' oldest son, William (1902\u201304), died at two years of age. Almost all of her children were involved in the film business and appeared with her in ''Over the Hill''.<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9F01E3DF1F31E433A2575BC1A96F9C946195D6CF NY Times: The Screen September 18, 1920 announcing the premier screening of ''Over the Hill'' with Mary Carr and her children]</ref>  They are as follows:\n*John Carr (January 2, 1904 \u2013 November 27, 1956)\n*Stephen Carr (April 23, 1906 \u2013 May 20, 1986)\n*[[Thomas Carr (director)|Thomas Carr]] (July 4, 1907 \u2013 April 23, 1997)\n*Rosemary Carr (October 2, 1910 \u2013 April 24, 1987)\n*Maybeth (Mary Elizabeth) Carr (May 4, 1912 \u2013 December 27, 1996) m. [[Pete Carpenter]]\n*Marie Luella Carr Walsh (October 18, 1899 \u2013 January 16, 1937)\n\n==Filmography==\n===Silent films===\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* ''[[The Shadow of Tragedy]]'' (1915 short)\n* ''[[The Mirror (1915 film)|The Mirror]]'' (1915 short) as Mrs. Carr\n* ''[[Blaming the Duck, or Ducking the Blame]]'' (1915 short) as Mrs. Carr\n* ''[[The City of Failing Light]]'' (1916) as Mrs. William Carr, '''lost'''\n* ''[[Souls in Bondage]]'' (1916) as Mrs. Carr, '''lost'''\n* ''[[Her Bleeding Heart]]'' (1916) as Mrs. Carr, '''lost'''\n* ''[[The Flames of Johannis]]'' (1916) as Mrs. Carr, '''lost'''\n* ''[[Love's Toll]]'' (1916) as Mrs. Carr, '''lost'''\n* ''[[The Light at Dusk]]'' (1916) as Mary Kennevan Carr, '''lost'''\n* ''[[The Barrier (1917 film)|The Barrier]]'' (1917) as Mary Kennevan Carr, '''lost'''\n* ''[[The Beloved Rogue (1918 film)|The Beloved Rogue]]'' (1918) '''lost''' (not to be confused with 1917 film ''[[Beloved Rogues]]'')\n* ''[[The Sign Invisible]]'' (1918) as Mary Kennevan Carr, '''lost'''\n* ''[[My Own United States]]'' (1918) as Mary Kennevan Carr, '''lost'''\n* ''[[To the Highest Bidder]]'' (1918) '''lost'''\n* ''[[The Birth of a Race]]''