d Irish Rose]]''\n| Brown\n|\n|-\n| 1948\n| ''[[Romance on the High Seas]]''\n| Ship Radio operator \n| Uncredited<br>Alternative title: ''It's Magic''\n|-\n| 1948\n| ''[[My Dear Secretary]]''\n| Sylvan Scott\n|\n|-\n| 1948\n| ''[[Jiggs and Maggie in Court]]''\n| Mr. Twiddle\n|\n|-\n| 1948\n| ''[[Last of the Wild Horses]]''\n| Curly, the cook\n|\n|-\n| 1949\n| ''[[Grand Canyon (1949 film)|Grand Canyon]]''\n| Halfnote\n|\n|-\n| 1949\n| ''[[Air Hostess (1949 film)|Air Hostess]]''\n| Ned Jenkins\n|\n|-\n| 1954\n| ''[[Living It Up]]''\n| Gift Shop Owner\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1954\n| ''[[A Star Is Born (1954 film)|A Star Is Born]]''\n| Artie Carver\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1954\n| ''[[White Christmas (1954 film)|White Christmas]]''\n| Mr. Herring\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1955\n| ''[[The Naked Dawn]]''\n| Cabaret Brawler\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1961\n| ''[[Madison Avenue (film)|Madison Avenue]]''\n| Dilbock\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1962\n| ''[[Billy Rose's Jumbo]]''\n| Driver\n|\n|-\n| 1962\n| ''[[The Chapman Report]]''\n| Simon\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1963\n| ''[[Come Blow Your Horn (film)|Come Blow Your Horn]]''\n| Clothing Store Manager\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1963\n| ''[[4 for Texas]]''\n| Bank Clerk\n|\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''[[My Fair Lady (film)|My Fair Lady]]''\n| Ascot Extra / Guest at Ball\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[Tickle Me]]''\n| Mr. Dabney\n|\n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[The Bounty Killer (film)|The Bounty Killer]]''\n| Minister\n|\n|-\n| 1966\n| ''[[The Chase (1966 film)|The Chase]]''\n| Mr. Siftifieus\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1966\n| ''[[Paradise, Hawaiian Style]]''\n| Mr. Cubberson\n|\n|-\n| 1968\n| ''[[Star! (film)|Star!]]''\n| First Salesman at Cartier's\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1968\n| ''[[I Love You, Alice B. Toklas!]]''\n| Funeral Director\n| Alternative title: ''Kiss My Butterfly''\n|-\n| 1970\n| ''[[The Great Bank Robbery (1969 film)|The Great Bank Robbery]]''\n| Rev. Simms\n|\n|-\n| 1970\n| ''[[Myra Breckinridge (film)|Myra Breckinridge]]''\n| Kid Barlow\n|\n|-\n| 1970\n| ''[[Suppose They Gave a War and Nobody Came]]''\n| Rev. Dinwood\n|\n|-\n| 1970\n| ''[[Dirty Dingus Magee]]''\n| Corporal\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[Support Your Local Gunfighter]]''\n| Storekeeper\n|\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Rock 'n' Roll High School]]''\n| School Board President\n| (final film role)\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\" \n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1954\n| ''[[I Married Joan]]''\n| Newsroom Walk Through\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1960\n| ''[[The Ann Sothern Show]]''\n| Swann\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Shirley Temple's Storybook]]''\n| Simon\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1960-1961\n| ''[[Lawman (TV series)|Lawman]]''\n| Ben Toomey\n| 8 episodes\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''[[Mickey (TV series)|Mickey]]''\n| Mr. Freebish\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1965\n| ''[[Burke's Law (1963 TV series)|Burke's Law]]''\n| Hubie\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Petticoat Junction]]''\n| Chef\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1967\n| ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]''\n| Irving Cash\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1972\n| ''[[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|Hawaii Five-O]]''\n| Minister\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''[[The Odd Couple (1970 TV series)|The Odd Couple]]''\n| Pops Belkin\n| 1 episode\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last= Maltin |first= Leonard |title= The Real Stars : Profiles and Interviews of Hollywood's Unsung Featured Players |chapter= Grady Sutton |pages= 256-277 |date= 2015 |edition= Sixth / eBook |orig-year=First published 1969 |type= softcover |publisher= CreateSpace Independent |location= Great Britain |isbn = 978-1-5116-4485-3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Grady Sutton}}\n*{{IMDb name|0840316}}\n*{{Amg name|69222}}\n*[http://www.virtual-history.com/movie/person/12011/grady-sutton Literature on Grady Sutton]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sutton, Grady}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male silent film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:People from Chattanooga, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Gay actors]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n\n\n{{US-film-actor-1900s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Inwind", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grady_Sutton"}
{"title_page": "Natalie Joyce", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{more footnotes|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Natalie Joyce\n| image       = Natalie Joyce photop325.jpg\n| birth_name  = Natalie Marie Johnson\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1902|11|06}} \n| birth_place = [[Norfolk, Virginia]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{dda|1992|11|09|1902|11|06}}\n| death_place = [[San Diego, California]], U.S.\n| occupation  = Actress\n| relatives   = [[Olive Borden]] (cousin)\n}}\n'''Natalie Joyce''' (born '''Natalie Marie Johnson'''; November 6, 1902 \u2013 November 9, 1992) was an American actress.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn as Natalie Marie Johnson on November 6, 1902, Joyce began her motion picture career in a series of [[two-reeler|two-reel]] comedies produced by the [[Christie Film Company]]. She was named one of the [[WAMPAS Baby Stars]] of 1925. In 1927 she co-starred with [[Tom Mix]] in ''[[The Circus Ace]]'' for [[Fox Film Corporation|Fox]] Pictures. In 1928 she was part of the cast of ''Through the Breakers''. Her first cousin was actress [[Olive Borden]]\n\nJoyce gave the [[Los Angeles Police Department]] important information in their quest to find two physicians wanted in the death of  22-year-old dancer [[Delphine Walsh]] in May 1929. Walsh died in a [[Glendale, California]] hospital following an illegal procedure,<ref>{{cite news|title=Witness in Death Trial Stirs Row|date=1929-08-31|work=The Los Angeles Times|page=A14}}</ref> the term then used for an [[abortion]].<ref name=harnish>{{cite web|url=http://ladailymirror.com/2006/12/18/whats-in-that-embalming-fluid/|title=Whats in That Embalming Fluid?|last=Harnish|first=Larry|date=2006-12-18|publisher=ladailymirror.com|accessdate=9 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter being away from making movies for a time, Joyce returned in ''[[Cock o' the Walk (1930 film)|Cock o' the Walk]]'' (1930), also known as ''The Soul of the Tango''. Produced by [[James Cruze]], the cast included [[Joseph Schildkraut]], [[Myrna Loy]], and [[Olive Tell]]. Joyce appeared in the [[Ingenue (stock character)|ingenue]] role.\n\nAfter retiring from acting Joyce worked as a bookkeeper and opened a hair salon. She married aviator William Morris Pryce in 1933.<ref>https://oliveborden1947.blogspot.com/2019/05/natalie-joyce.html</ref> The couple had one son named Michael. Joyce died in [[San Diego, California]] in 1992, aged 90.\n\n==Partial filmography==\n* ''[[The Circus Ace]]'' (1927)\n* ''[[Whispering Sage]]'' (1927)\n* ''[[Daredevil's Reward]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[A Girl in Every Port (1928 film)|A Girl in Every Port]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Naughty Baby (film)|Naughty Baby]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Through the Breakers]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Pals of the Prairie]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[Laughing at Death]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[The Man from Nevada (1929 film)|The Man from Nevada]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[Times Square (1929 film)|Times Square]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[Sailor's Holiday (1929 film)|Sailor's Holiday]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[Cock o' the Walk (1930 film)|Cock o' the Walk]]'' (1930) *lost film\n* ''[[Police Court (film)|Police Court]]'' (1932)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[[Los Angeles Times]], ''Christie Comedies Players Announced'', August 24, 1924, Page B37.\n*Los Angeles Times, ''Wampas Baby Stars of 1925'', January 4, 1925, Page B1.\n*Los Angeles Times, ''Picturetone to be Used'', August 14, 1928, Page A8.\n*Los Angeles Times, ''Dancer's Death Quiz Continues'', May 8, 1929, Page A12.\n*Los Angeles Times, ''Cruz Adds To Cast'', February 5, 1930, Page A12.\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | author=[[Michael G. Ankerich]] | title=Dangerous Curves atop Hollywood Heels: The Lives, Careers, and Misfortunes of 14 Hard-Luck Girls of the Silent Screen| publisher=BearManor | year=2010 | isbn=1-59393-605-2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Natalie Joyce}}\n*{{IMDb name|0431580}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joyce, Natalie}}\n[[Category:Actresses from Virginia]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American silent film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actors from Norfolk, Virginia]]\n[[Category:1902 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:WAMPAS Baby Stars]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{no footnotes|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Natalie Joyce\n| image       = Natalie Joyce photop325.jpg\n| birth_name  = Natalie Marie Johnson\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1902|11|06}} \n| birth_place = [[Norfolk, Virginia]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{dda|1992|11|09|1902|11|06}}\n| death_place = [[San Diego, California]], U.S.\n| occupation  = Actress\n| relatives   = [[Olive Borden]] (cousin)\n}}\n'''Natalie Joyce''' (born '''Natalie Marie Johnson'''; November 6, 1902 \u2013 November 9, 1992) was an American actress.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn as Natalie Marie Johnson on November 6, 1902, Joyce began her motion picture career in a series of [[two-reeler|two-reel]] comedies produced by the [[Christie Film Company]]. She was named one of the [[WAMPAS Baby Stars]] of 1925. In 1927 she co-starred with [[Tom Mix]] in ''[[The Circus Ace]]'' for [[Fox Film Corporation|Fox]] Pictures. In 1928 she was part of the cast of ''Through the Breakers''. Her first cousin was actress [[Olive Borden]]  \n\nJoyce gave the [[Los Angeles Police Department]] important information in their quest to find two physicians wanted in the death of  22-year-old dancer [[Delphine Walsh]] in May 1929. Walsh died in a [[Glendale, California]] hospital following an illegal procedure,<ref>{{cite news|title=Witness in Death Trial Stirs Row|date=1929-08-31|work=The Los Angeles Times|page=A14}}</ref> the term then used for an [[abortion]].<ref name=harnish>{{cite web|url=http://ladailymirror.com/2006/12/18/whats-in-that-embalming-fluid/|title=Whats in That Embalming Fluid?|last=Harnish|first=Larry|date=2006-12-18|publisher=ladailymirror.com|accessdate=9 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter being away from making movies for a time, Joyce returned in ''[[Cock o' the Walk (1930 film)|Cock o' the Walk]]'' (1930), also known as ''The Soul of the Tango''. Produced by [[James Cruze]], the cast included [[Joseph Schildkraut]], [[Myrna Loy]], and [[Olive Tell]]. Joyce appeared in the [[Ingenue (stock character)|ingenue]] role.\n\nAfter retiring from acting Joyce worked as a bookkeeper and opened a hair salon. She married aviator William Morris Pryce in 1933.<ref>https://oliveborden1947.blogspot.com/2019/05/natalie-joyce.html</ref> The couple had one son named Michael. Joyce died in [[San Diego, California]] in 1992, aged 90.\n\n==Partial filmography==\n* ''[[The Circus Ace]]'' (1927)\n* ''[[Whispering Sage]]'' (1927)\n* ''[[Daredevil's Reward]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[A Girl in Every Port (1928 film)|A Girl in Every Port]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Naughty Baby (film)|Naughty Baby]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Through the Breakers]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Pals of the Prairie]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[Laughing at Death]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[The Man from Nevada (1929 film)|The Man from Nevada]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[Times Square (1929 film)|Times Square]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[Sailor's Holiday]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[Cock o' the Walk (1930 film)|Cock o' the Walk]]'' (1930) *lost film\n* ''[[Police Court (film)|Police Court]]'' (1932)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[[Los Angeles Times]], ''Christie Comedies Players Announced'', August 24, 1924, Page B37.\n*Los Angeles Times, ''Wampas Baby Stars of 1925'', January 4, 1925, Page B1.\n*Los Angeles Times, ''Picturetone to be Used'', August 14, 1928, Page A8.\n*Los Angeles Times, ''Dancer's Death Quiz Continues'', May 8, 1929, Page A12.\n*Los Angeles Times, ''Cruz Adds To Cast'', February 5, 1930, Page A12.\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | author=[[Michael G. Ankerich]] | title=Dangerous Curves atop Hollywood Heels: The Lives, Careers, and Misfortunes of 14 Hard-Luck Girls of the Silent Screen| publisher=BearManor | year=2010 | isbn=1-59393-605-2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Natalie Joyce}}\n*{{IMDb 