t. John Hayes\n| [[Budd Boetticher]]\n| WarnerColor\n|- \n| ''[[Ride Lonesome]]''\n| Ben Brigade\n| [[Budd Boetticher]]\n| CinemaScope<br />Eastmancolor\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1960\n| ''[[Comanche Station]]''\n| Jefferson Cody\n| [[Budd Boetticher]]\n| CinemaScope<br />Eastmancolor\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1962\n| ''[[Ride the High Country]]''\n| Gil Westrum\n| [[Sam Peckinpah]]\n| CinemaScope<br />Metrocolor<br />Filmed with Panavision, released in CinemaScope<br />Released in the United Kingdom under the title ''Guns in the Afternoon''\n|}\n\n===Box office ranking===\nAt the height of his career, exhibitors voted Scott among the most popular stars in the country:\n*1949 - 12th (US)<ref>Hope Tops Crosby At the Boxoffice\nBy Richard L. Coe. The Washington Post (1923-1954) [Washington, D.C] 30 Dec 1949: 19.</ref>\n*1950 - 10th (US)\n*1951 - 7th (US)\n*1952 - 10th (US)\n*1953 - 10th (US)\n*1954 - 22nd (US)\n*1955 - 22nd (US)\n*1956 - 24th (US)\n\n==Short films==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"100%\"\n! width=\"5%\"| Year\n! width=\"20%\"| Title\n! width=\"20%\"| Role\n! width=\"20%\"| Director\n! class=unsortable | Notes\n|-\n| 1935\n|''Pirate Party on Catalina Isle''\n| Himself\n| Gene Burdette\n| [[Technicolor]]\n|-\n| 1941\n| ''Meet the Stars #6: Stars at Play''\n| Himself\n| Gene Parsons\n|\n|-\n| 1951\n| ''Screen Snapshots: Hollywood Goes Western''\n| Himself\n| Ralph Staub\n|\n|-\n| 1953\n| ''Screen Snapshots: Men of the West''\n| Himself\n| Ralph Staub\n|\n|}\n\n==Television==\n\n[[Randolph Scott]]'s only venture into television (other than an appearance on ''Celebrity Golf'') was in the late 1950s as the host of a proposed series entitled ''Randolph Scott's Theater of the West''.    The episode starred [[Scott Brady]] as a lawman trying to escape a criminal past.  The series was never sold and this one and only episode was never aired.\n\n==Footnotes==\n<references/>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Randolph Scott Filmography}}\n[[Category:Male actor filmographies|Scott, Randolph]]\n[[Category:American filmographies|Scott, Randolph]]\n", "text_old": "'''[[Randolph Scott]]''' (1898\u20131987) appeared in over 100 feature films in his career.  These films are listed below.\n\n==Feature films==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" width=\"100%\"\n! width=\"5%\"| Year\n! width=\"20%\"| Title\n! width=\"20%\"| Role\n! width=\"20%\"| Director\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1928\n|''[[Sharp Shooters]]''\n|  Foreign Serviceman in Moroccan Cafe\n| [[John G. Blystone]]\n| Released in the United Kingdom under the title ''Three Naval Rascals''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"6\" | 1929\n|''[[Weary River]]''\n| Man in Audience\n| [[Frank Lloyd]]\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Far Call]]''\n| Helms\n| [[Allan Dwan]]\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Black Watch]]''\n| Bit Part\n| [[John Ford]]\n| Released in the United Kingdom under the title ''King of the Khyber Rifles''\n|-\n|''[[Sailor's Holiday]]''\n| Undetermined Role\n| [[Fred C. Newmeyer]]\n|\n|- \n|''[[The Virginian (1929 film)|The Virginian]]''\n| Rider extra\n| [[Victor Fleming]]\n|\n|-\n|''[[Dynamite (1929 film)|Dynamite]]''\n| Undetermined Role\n| [[Cecil B. DeMille]]\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1930\n|''[[Born Reckless (1930 film)|Born Reckless]]''\n| Joan's Rejected Suitor\n| John Ford<br />Andrew Benniston\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1931\n|''[[Women Men Marry (1931 film)|Women Men Marry]]''\n| Steve Bradley\n| Charles Hitchinson\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"5\" | 1932\n|''[[Sky Bride]]''\n| Captain Frank Robertson\n| Stephen Roberts\n|\n|-\n|''[[A Successful Calamity]]''\n| Larry Rivers, the Polo Coach\n| [[John G. Adolfi]]\n|\n|- \n|''[[Heritage of the Desert (1932 film)|Heritage of the Desert]]''\n| Jack Hare\n| [[Henry Hathaway]]\n| Reissued under the title ''When the West Was Young''\n|-\n|''[[Hot Saturday]]''\n| Bill Fadden\n| [[William A. Seiter]]\n|\n|- \n|''[[Wild Horse Mesa (1932 film)|Wild Horse Mesa]]''\n| Chane Weymer\n| Henry Hathaway\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" r