{"title_page": "Slim Summerville", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}{{Infobox person\n| name          = Slim Summerville\n| image         = Douglas Fairbanks Jr. Slim Summerville Little Accident 1930.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = Summerville (right) in ''Little Accident'' (1930)\n| birth_name    = George Joseph Somerville \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1892|7|10}}\n| birth_place   = [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1946|1|5|1892|7|1}}\n| death_place   = [[Laguna Beach, California]], U.S.\n| occupation    = Actor & Director\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Gertrude Roell|1927|1936|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Eleanor Brown|1937|1946}}\n| children      = Elliot Brown\n| yearsactive   = 1912\u20131946\n}}\n\n'''George Joseph Somerville''' (July 10, 1892 &ndash; January 5, 1946), known professionally as '''Slim Summerville''', was an American [[film actor]], best known as a [[comedy]] [[performer]].<ref>{{cite book | first=Ray | last=Stuart | title=Immortals of the Screen | page=218 | publisher=Sherbourne Press | year=1965}}\n</ref>\n\n==Life==\nBorn George Joseph Somerville in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]], his mother died when he was five.<ref name=pittpress>{{cite news |title=Sad-Looking Slim Summerville Never Hoped To Be Funny - Just Can't Help It |first=Paul |last=Harrison |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=bnYbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1ksEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3961,5297533&dq=slim+summerville&hl=en |newspaper=The Pittsburgh Press |date=13 July 1936 |accessdate=8 February 2012}}</ref>\nMoving from [[New Mexico]] to Canada to [[Oklahoma]], he had a [[nomad]]ic upbringing.<ref name=pittpress/>\n\nHe married Gertrude Martha Roell on 19 November 1927.<ref name=warsaw/><ref name=spokesman>{{cite news |title=Sad Slim Summerville Loses Wife at Court |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BChWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=r-MDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4465,534233&dq=slim+and+summerville+and+divorce&hl=en |newspaper=The Spokesman-Review |date=2 October 1936 |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref>  In early 1932, the Summervilles adopted a four-week-old baby boy whom they christened Elliott George.<ref>{{cite news |title=Slum Summerville of Movies Adopts Baby |url=http://hollywoodheyday.blogspot.com/2008/10/february-6-1932.html |newspaper=Associated Press |date=6 February 1932 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref>  The couple divorced in September 1936,<ref name=spokesman/><ref>{{cite news |title=Wife Divorces Film Comedian |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jXYbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0ksEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4438,1061328&dq=slim+and+summerville+and+elliot+and+george&hl=en |newspaper=The Pittsburgh Press |date=2 October 1936 |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> and he then married Eleanor Brown (also a divorcee), who was his nurse, who cared for him when he was sick. She fell in love and married him in 1937, to keep him from getting sick again.<ref name=warsaw/><ref name=montreal/>\n\nSummerville died of a [[stroke]] on January 5, 1946 in [[Laguna Beach, California]].<ref name=warsaw/><ref name=sarasota/><ref>{{cite journal | journal=Motion Picture Herald | publisher=Quigley Pub. Co. | year=1946}}</ref> He is buried at [[Inglewood Park Cemetery]] in [[South Los Angeles]] community of [[Inglewood, California]]. Twenty years after his death, his beach front house on Sleepy Hollow Lane in Laguna Beach was converted into the Beach House restaurant,<ref>{{cite book | title=Life is a beach: a vacationer's guide to the West Coast | first1=Parke | last1=Puterbaugh | first2=Alan | last2=Bisbort | publisher=McGraw-Hill | year=1988 | page=74}}</ref> now the Driftwood Kitchen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yelp.com/biz/driftwood-kitchen-laguna-beach-2|title=Driftwood Kitchen - Laguna Beach, CA|website=Yelp|access-date=2016-05-22}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSummerville's first [[Job (role)|job]] was as a [[Courier|messenger]] for the [[Canadian Pacific Railway#Telegraph|Canadian Pacific Telegraphs]] in [[Chatham, Ontario]] where he lived with his [[English people|English]] [[grandparents]].<ref name=montreal>{{cite news |title=Lanky Screen Comic Gets Romantic 'Break' |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=eHYtAAAAIBAJ&sjid=i5gFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5799,2888429&dq=slim+and+summerville+and+eleanor&hl=en |newspaper=The Montreal Gazette |date=17 September 1941 |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe was working as a [[poolroom]] [[porter (carrier)|porter]] when found by [[Edgar Kennedy]],<ref name=warsaw>{{cite news |title=Stroke Fatal to Movie Star - \"Slim\" Summerville Dies Suddenly |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=6x5HAAAAIBAJ&sjid=nXoMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3639,349976&dq=slim+summerville+dies&hl=en |newspaper=Warsaw Daily Union |date=7 January 1946 |accessdate=8 February 2012}}</ref> who took him to [[Mack Sennett]] where he started at $3.50 per day.<ref name=sarasota>{{cite news |title=Slim Summerville, Of The Movies, Dies |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SOMcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mWQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2978,443417&dq=slim+summerville&hl=en |newspaper=Sarasota Herald-Tribune |date=7 January 1946 |accessdate=8 February 2012}}</ref>\nHis first role was as a \"[[Keystone Kops|Keystone Kop]]\" in ''[[Hoffmeyer's Legacy]]'' (1912).\n\nHis tall, gangly appearance was well utilized in numerous short [[comedy films]] during the [[silent film]] era, and in addition to his many acting roles, he directed more than 50 [[short films]].\n\nOccasionally, he played in dramatic films, such as ''[[All Quiet on the Western Front (1930 film)|All Quiet on the Western Front]]'' (1930) and ''[[Jesse James (1939 film)|Jesse James]]'' (1939). However, he was most successful in comedy films, including several with [[ZaSu Pitts]]. He also played in films with [[Shirley Temple]], ''[[Captain January (1936 film)|Captain January]]'' (1936) and ''[[Rebecca of Sunnybrook Farm (1938 film)|Rebecca of Sunnybrook Farm]]'' (1938).\n\n==Legacy==\nFor his contribution to the motion picture industry, Slim Summerville has a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] at 6409 Hollywood Blvd.<ref>[http://www.walkoffame.com/slim-summerville Slim Summerville]. ''[[Hollywood Walk of Fame]]''. Retrieved 2012-02-11</ref>\n\nHe was inducted into the New Mexico Entertainment Hall of Fame in 2012.\n\n==Selected filmography==\n{{Div col}}\n* ''[[Hoffmeyer's Legacy]]'' (1912, Short) as Keystone Kop (uncredited)\n* ''[[Mabel's Busy Day]]'' (1914, Short) as Policeman (uncredited)\n* ''[[Fatty and the Heiress]]'' (1914, Short)\n* ''[[A Rowboat Romance]]'' (1914, Short)\n* ''[[Laughing Gas (1914 film)|Laughing Gas]]'' (1914, Short) as Pedestrian / Patient\n* ''[[Those Happy Days (1914 film)|Those Happy Days]]'' (1914, Short) as Cop (uncredited)\n* ''[[Lover's Luck]]'' (1914, Short) as Villager\n* ''[[Dough and Dynamite]]'' (1914) as Striking Baker (uncredited)\n* ''[[Tillie's Punctured Romance (1914 film)|Tillie's Punctured Romance]]'' (1914) as Policeman / Guest in Restaurant (uncredited)\n* ''[[Leading Lizzie Astray]]'' (1914, Short) as Dancing Cafe Patron (uncredited)\n* ''[[Fatty's Magic Pants]]'' (1914, Short) as Cop (uncredited)\n* ''[[Fatty and Minnie He-Haw]]'' (1914, Short) as Railroad Guard (uncredited)\n* ''[[Fatty's New Role]]'' (1915, Short) as Bartender\n* ''[[That Little Band of Gold]]'' (1915, Short) as Waiter / Audience Member (uncredited)\n* ''[[Their Social Splash]]'' (1915, Short) as Harold - the Groom\n* ''[[Her Painted Hero]]'' (1915, Short) as A Bill Poster\n* ''[[Fatty and the Broadway Stars]]'' (1915, Short) as Striking Carpenter\n* ''[[Hearts and Sparks]]'' (1916, Short) as The Moneylender's Pit Crewman\n* ''Are Witnesses Safe?'' (1917)\n* ''[[Skirts (film)|Skirts]]'' (1921)\n* ''[[Hello, 'Frisco]]'' (1924, also directed, Short) as Slim\n* ''[[The Texas Streak]]'' (1926) as Swede\n* ''[[The Denver Dude]]'' (1927) as Slim Jones\n* ''[[The Beloved Rogue]]'' (1927) as Jehan\n* ''[[Hey! Hey! Cowboy]]'' (1927) as Spike Doolin\n* ''[[Painted Ponies]]'' (1927) as Beanpole\n* ''[[The Chinese Parrot (film)|The 